If you are building an FDL-2+ please visit the main FDL-2 thing first. Print all the files in that thing and this one.

Getting them tight enough so that they don't come loose without stripping them is challenging. I had similar issues with the spinner set screw, but everything seems to be working fine now. One must also be careful with the wires that go to the voltmeter. Those are the only 3 nitpicky complaints. Nicer M2 screws is the only one that would be nice to correct. Son loves it. description.text:
I saw a video of someone using something similar and I suggested to my wife that this might be a good thing to print. She said, "I would love to be able to hand those to potential customers for my 31 business." So I mixed this up with openscad. Note that the STL file includes her name, phone number, and so forth. She sells "31", a line of nice, personalized bags. If you want to be nice to me :-) print the stl as is and give it to whoever in your household makes bag buying decisions. If you are just interested, I know she will be happy to talk to you about the bags.

Anyway, this was whipped up in openSCAD as has most of my stuff recently. I created a guitar pick shape, cut letters out of it for her name and phone number, and added a thing that holds between your fingers. If you are a kitchen pro, when you use a knife, you curl your fingers under. With this gadget, the way the fingerholder works manes you more likely to hold your fingers under. The point of the shield is that you are supposed to be able to hide your fingers behind the shield so that you don't cut yourself if you mishandle the knife.

I am mentioning this - I specifically disclaim any warranty or liability. It is your job to determine if this shield will provide you adequate coverage, to test it, and to come to the final determination about whether to use it. My liability is limited to the amount you paid me for these files, that is, zero. If you don't think the item is suitable, you can redesign it however you see fit. I have included the openSCAD - or you can create your own. I will ask that you do not use this for commercial purposes or remix it. Well, let me clarify that. If you print the supplied STL without any changes, you can sell them. But if you want to change the message on them, and use them for commercial purposes, contact me and we will talk.

Note: I have added a second fingerguard stl with a more central holder. One person might want one, one the other style. Either could be generated by the same openSCAD source with parameter changes.

This should need no post processing. With the large area touching the bed it should not need raft or brim, so when you remove it from a relatively clean bed you are done.

openSCAD - think of your project in shapes

The shield was out of an old science fiction story where a culture considered the circle sacred - they needed a non-circular shape that could, none the less, be able to be used as a roller to move large objects. The equilateral triangle with line length arcs struck from each vertex was the solution. Then i had to decide whether to add a ring or a post - I decided on the post. So that was a rectangle and a triangular piece, and each was rounded using Minkowsky summation.

The source is included. If you don't want to print them with my wife's name and number on them, just grab a copy of openSCAD and alter them.

Coloring

In an effort to use the last half meter of my yellow PLA filament, I followed it into the bowden tube with the purple filament. You can see the result. A single layer of yellow printed as gold with the purple background - but where there was enough for a second layer, the purple didn't show through, although the print looks brass or golden and not yellow. Silly color wheel.

description.text:
Hello everyone,

I decided to release my design to the world. Here is my take on the Nerf Apollo Pump conversion, after looking online at a few different 3d printed Nerf Apollo pump conversions, I decided to take tidbits of each that I liked and compile them into my own design. This whole design and build are a work in progress and I have not tested this set up in a Nerf War yet. I have printed out a previous iteration of the design, of which you can see the attached pictures of. The design hasn't changed too much since that iteration. Make sure to set up your slicer to print in the best way you know possible to reduce supports and bed adhesion. Experiment/print at your own risk!

I have also designed a stock attachment. Please excuse the tape on the stock, I printed them in two pieces then epoxied puttied together because I was testing fit.

I appreciate any feedback/comments!

Please feel free to tip me or donate to me for the work on this design if you are so inclined to do so. Paypal: paypal.me/counterstrikegamer44

Additional hardware (that I used):
(2) 11"-11.5" long 0.5" wide metal flatbar (Can find at any hardware store, cut down to size at home. I used steel but aluminum will probably work)
(5) M6 x 1.00 x 50mm Hex Head Bolts

Tips:

  • Do the lock removal mod for the apollo or else you may have some nasty jams!
  • When connecting the picatinny to barrel, you have to drill a hole through the top of the barrel so the bolt can go through.
  • Make sure you sand down the barrel to avoid that zip-zip sound when priming!
  • Drill holes accurately in the metal flat bar in order to get a smooth prime
  • Beware of friction between the sliding mechanism and the barrel ( I ran into some issues there, make it work!)
  • The grip is held on the sliding mechanism by friction alone between the two parts, epoxy or some type of fastener or glue can make sure it stays!
  • The bottom of the slide has a picatinny rail attachment ( I previously put it there so I could attach a vertical foregrip of my own, but too much of a moment was created on the sliding mechanism and the barrel increasing friction to the point of being unprimable since the slide corner would dig itself into the barrel)

description.text:
So, thanks to my kids.... I've been supplying the locals with Fidget Spinners. Using the typical Skateboard Bearings for weights, and Ceramic "Hybrid" bearings for the center bearings....

But I kept thinking there had to be a better way. I had seen ball bearing spinners on here, but they required you to heat the bearing and melt it into place. I started worrying about younger children getting the ball out of this type of spinner and swallowing them. So I decided to model up a "Ball socket" for the ball bearings. once installed, they swivel inside the ball socket just like a ball socket joint.

To install them, takes a fair amount of force (hence the relief at the end of the stem) and a small vice, or a arbor press works the best..... however, if your plastic is flexible enough... a quick tap with a Hammer will install them as well... just be careful, it can crack your hard work!

They take standard .500" steel ball bearings (available for as low as .10 a piece) and I like to use Hybrid 608 ball bearings (Which will give me 4+ minutes of hand table spins)..... But any skateboard/rollerblade bearing will work.

Choose the approperate file based on your layer height (100 vs 200 Microns). What I found is the 200 Micron "Steps" inside the ball socket required the clearance to be more than if you print at 100 Microns. if you print the 200 Micron file at 100 Microns, it will work just fine, but the balls are looser. visa versa, if you print the 100 Micron file at 200 Microns, the ball socket will be too tight.

I created a compact solar-powered rechargeable battery that can be taken on-the-go and used to charge smartphones. This project is made up of two elements: the circuit and 3D-printed enclosure.

My step-by-step process is documented on this Google site:
https://sites.google.com/s/0B5-B9G7QADdmTkQxOVBZaXVzZ1k/p/0B5-B9G7QADdmUFpJa2RvSU4wQ28/edit

Why Solar Power? 1) Solar energy is the most abundant energy source on the planet.
2) Technological improvements and research have resulted in tremendous drops in the cost of solar power.
3) Due to dropping costs and environmental factors like global warming and air pollution, the solar energy industry has been the fastest-growing industry in the U.S. in recent years.
For more information, visit: https://cleantechnica.com/solar-power/

Step 1: Constructing the enclosure I used Tinkercad to construct my enclosure. It took a lot of time and patience to get precise dimensions, and you can find all the specifics on my website. I have provided the .STL file, so if you would like to recreate this project, you may download and print the box and lid. Step 2: Assembling the circuit 1) Solder the capacitor onto the solar charger. Bend the capacitor before soldering so it will fit more compactly onto the charger.
2) Soldered the leads of the capacitor to the charger. Solder the JST connector to the LOAD side of the charger (red wire to LOAD, black wire to GND).
3) Solder the USB port onto the PowerBoost.
4) Prepare a slide switch by soldering two silicone-coated wires to two adjacent pins on the switch. Apply and shrink heat shrink tubing onto the connections.
5) Prepare the solar panel by replacing the barrel jack and shrinking heat shrink tubing over the soldered area for additional stability.
6) Solder the two end wires of the switch to EN and GND on the PowerBoost.
7) The green light on the PowerBoost should turn on. Assembling the Battery Box 1) Attach the battery to the lid of the box with velcro or double-sided foam tape.
2) After all the soldering is completed, plug the charger's JST wire into the PowerBoost and the battery into the BATT plug on the charger. Use hot glue to attach the solar charger and PowerBoost to the support boosters and to keep the switch in place.
3) Use one screw in each corner of the lid to screw the box shut and plug in the solar panel. Plug the USB cord into the box and phone and flip the switch. Your phone should begin to charge! The completed circuit The circuit in the enclosure The functioning solar-powered battery charging an iPad

Materials for circuit Note: These materials can be purchased from Adafruit or Amazon:

Print instructions:
  • Take STL (or generate suitable version from scad).
  • Process it with your favorite slicer (I use skeinforge).
  • Open resulting GCODE file.
  • Find where the last layer of nut chamber ends.
  • Add some fancy G-codes here. I used a couple of slow movements:
    • ;Insert nut here
    G1 X130 Y0 Z14.04 F2400
    ;Retract filament even more
    G1 E248.442 F1000 ; USE YOUR E-value HERE! (I used last E-value - 3)
    G1 X130 Y150 F2400
    G1 X140 Y150 F240
    G1 X140 Y140 F240
    G1 X140 Y150 F240
    G1 X130 Y150 F240
    G1 X33.543 Y55.927 Z14.04 F2400.0
    ;Return additional retraction
    G1 E251.442 F1000 ; USE YOUR E-value HERE! (I used last E-value)
    ; It gave me enough time to insert the nut into the chamber. Plastic is hot and soft at this point, so insertion is very easy.
  • Print and watch. When printhead moves away from the part, insert your nut in the chamber.
  • Continue printing.
  • Enjoy.
    • I don't like the drilling idea, because it creates some PTFE dust, which can clog your nozzle - PTFE doesn't melt at ABS/PLA temperatures. So here goes my solution.
    Assembly instructions:
  • Take appropriate hex wrench. I used 3mm hex wrench for my 3mm filament tube.
  • Insert it into the adapter.
  • Push wrench into the end of PTFE tube (see the picture). It should put on tightly.
  • Push the tube into adapter. Screw it into the nut. Hex wrench is very helpful here, because it has pretty tight grip and a lever, so you can turn the tube easier.
  • Pull the hex wrench out.
  • Enjoy.

description.text:
I have a Davinci Pro.
It has LEDs inside to light up the chamber. The chamber is nice and bright, except right at the nozzle. It is always in a shadow.
I made this clip on LED holder. It clips on the front 2 linear bearing housings and you can rotate it around a little bit.
The LED strips run on 12vdc. I don't know if there is 12vdc in this printer or not. I have a tiny video camera inside my printer so I can watch my print progress remotely. It runs on 12vdc. Too easy. I got a 12vdc splitter and powered my LEDs from the camera's 12vdc power supply.
I made 2 versions of this LED mount.
One for a LED strip, cut down to 3 LEDs. It measures 50mm X 8mm.
The other version has (2) 5mm holes in it for 5mm LEDs.

And looking at the picture, yes, it is a Pro.
BUT
I use S3D, E3D V6, and a PrintinZ build plate.

DISCOVERY: If the little ears break off when you clip it on to the bearing housings, then print it again, and increase your infill. 20% might be too low. Try 50%.

REVISION - I beefed up the ear that broke at 20%, it' stronger there now but I would still use an infill of 50%.
I made 3 versions.
LED strip
2 led's
5050 3 led module

Be careful with the 5050 module bracket. It hangs down lower than the other 2 and there might be interference when setting your z offset or zeroing your axes.

title: Finger, Robotic, Modular, pull string actuated

description.text: Here are some modular finger joints that I designed that worked really well. Was trying to imitate the movement of the finger withing the space of the finger. They seem pretty tough and stay together well. They use Hillman Fasteners extension spring 540213, #71, 5/32" x 15/16", .016" wire, I got from True Value Hardware Store. The finger joints snap together in the out of joint position. I used some weed wacker twine as a pull string. The finger tip has an angled tube inside, you can push the twine right in under the finger nail, it is held in place with a 6-32 set screw deep in the finger tip. You will need to cut some threads with a 6-32 tap. There are hopefully enough sizes to make a realistic size hand if needed. I have included a knuckle maybe you can adapt to a hand. There are two different joint angles the finger tip is a 60 degree angle but you can use it with the 90 degree angle. The finger joints are 90 degree angle. I tried using these with the string pulley servo winch in my things, but it didn't have enough pull with cheap servos. I don't think you can make a device small enough but strong enough to pull 5 strings within say the confines of a forearm. My servo winch will work with 1/8" nylon air brake tubing with the weed wacker line inside for a remote operation. Hope someone can incorporate this design into a usable hand. The springs stay in well, but if the spring shaft breaks a little model glue does the trick. A paper clip wire end helps get the spring in it's hole. Probably pretty useless, but they worked pretty close to a human finger, all the joints want to move the same and with the thicker weed wacker string it had some push back also. If you change the scale, you change the spring size. I may have some smaller finger sizes already drawn if you need them for little finger. These are patterned from the size of my hand, I have attached a picture of hand bones and a trace of my hand with joint measurements. Anyway I thought these where really cool to mess with. Hopefully they will spark an idea in someone else. Enjoy!

title: Wheel Bearing Grease Packing Tool adapter / No Zert

description.text:
Had a desire to repack wheel bearings with grease quicker than by disassembling the hub.

Of course, there are commercially available​ devices to accomplish the task of easily adding grease between the two bearings of the hub. All that I saw were manufactured from metal and had a grease fitting / zert installed. Some also included a back plate. All were more expensive than I was willing to pay for this type of tool and it's function.

I concluded the pressures could be contained with a 3D printed adapter tool. No back plate needed if custom made with tight tolerance.
Made with supports but that seemed to disfigure the threads of both parts. Fortunately, these materials can be fused together with a little heat applied. Made with PLA just cause it was loaded.

May have to look into chemical reactions for assurance in future builds. If I take the time to redesign, I would move the center distribution area closer to the grease fitting to create angled dispersion tubes resulting in less grease to "prime" the tool and potentially reducing internal pressure

description.text: A hand spinner. Work with bearing R188:6.35x12.7x4.76mm.

The simple undulating link created by the function

function f(t,h=height) =
[ cos(t), sin(t), h x sin(2*t)];

can be connected in a matrix to form a chain or mesh. The OpenSCAD code previews quite quickly but rendering is slow because each link added has to be checked for intersection with all the others, leading an O(N^2) performance.

Most chains I've seen use flat links but this curved link allows a flatter and uniform mesh because the link works bidirectionally. Some chain mail uses a form of this link, but OpenSCAD allows the shape of the link and its orientation to be parameterised.

To make the mesh more printable, subtract a base positioned below the links to flatten the feet of each link.

description.text: I designed this bracelet to bridge the gap of requiring a tight chain bracelet to anchor the long plastic piece used in the Knick Finger, my bracelet has four equally spaced holes within the approximate location of the base knuckles to help provide tension if more than one Knick Finger is required. For example if you have three missing fingers, a pinky, ring, and middle finger, you would use this bracelet to tie a single knot instead of having to attach three of the long plastic pieces for each finger in order to articulate the joint.

Notes:

Detail may not be too important unless you add some decorative studs or something since you can clean up the holes with a drill bit, but strength is very important if you decide to use PLA instead of a rubber filament.

You're going to need some masking tape!

Just measured my wrist diameter for bracelet size, did this by wrapping tape around the protruding bone on my wrist and carefully cutting the tape in half vertically from the wrist to leave a long section of tape lace, divide the length of this lace by 3.14 to get an approximate max diameter of the bracelet then adjust for comfort.

Precision Drill Bit Hole is printed in 1 mm diameter, with a 1.5 mm countersink at the back facing the elbow to allow knots to sit flush inside the bracelet. Dyneema is about .3 mm in diameter so you shouldn't need to resize the holes very much, just do a bit of light cleanup work inside so the fishing line doesn't snag. SpiderWire Braided Fishing Line - $15 I use 65 lb strength for making bullwhip crackers, they consistently reach speeds of up to 800 mph so this should definitely satisfy the strength criteria for the Knick Finger. Can be bought at most sporting good stores for about $15 a roll of 125 yards. Much cheaper than buying frilly, expensive bow string for about $80 a spool, and it does not need to be waxed to work with! Flexible Rubber Filament (Optional) While a harder, more rigid piece seems better suited the wrist requires a fair range of motion, and the bracelet must be able to resist sudden force if it snags on something by accident. I have heard positive things about NinjaFlex, but experiment to your liking. Digital Caliper Doesn't need to be fancy, just good enough. Harbor Freight has them for about $9, less if you use their frequent online discounts.

This thing is a more simple setup, compared to https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:771004
Gear wheels are included and attached to a frame.
https://youtu.be/oOeriEbkMsY
For the miniature geared dc motor, a 9 volt battery is fixed with a tie wrap or a piece of double sided adhesive foam tape..
https://youtu.be/-gS8GaNyc9I
You might need to rotate the body to the normal position before printing. It is a good idea to trim the shaft openings in the frame after printing with a 4 mm drill.
The square shafts are driven gently into one of the leg wheels with a light hammer. Only gentle force should be applied. If a shaft breaks, remove it with an M3 bolt in the other side of the shaft opening and use a hammer to remove the broken part. When installing the wheels at the other side, the leg bolts should be opposite. Depending on the tolerances of your printer, it might be necessary to remove some material from the shaft ends using sandpaper, until they slip into position with reasonable friction. Eventually use a rotary tool to rotate the shaft and clamp sandpaper to the rotating end, applying pressure with your fingers. The legs are secured by a lock nut. The on/off switch goes into the tail. If your buggy walks backward, simply reverse the motor wires. A drop of oil on the moving parts reduces friction. The shell is fixed with two M3x50 bolts and separated from the frame with two printed spacers. If the legs are not exactly synchronized, buggy gets a funny wobly walk as demonstrated in the movie of the test walk.

description.text:
I created an along_with module and wrote an example of dragon scales. Then, I thought: "Can I use OpenSCAD to model a dragon?"

The thing here is a proof of concept so its code is quick and dirty. It's not perfect but works. If you want to create something like this and don't know how to start from scratch, it might be a reference.

The wave base is created by the bezier_surface function. The curve of the dragon body is created by the bezier_curve function. I leave the x coordinates of several control points as parameters for trying it in Customizer. If you change their values, the dragon will swing in different ways.

There are other modules in the code. If you are interested in them, check my dotSCAD library.

This is not intended to be printed!

It's only a 3D shape of this type of heatbed:
http://www.ebay.com/itm/131746269006

You can easily find other sellers on ebay with the same item, I'm not advertising, just pointing an example.

Make a hangar for your board that fits your board, printer and wall.

  1. Choose "Wheel diameter" and "Upright height" as principle measurements. Ensure Smooth is off. Upright height must fit on your printer bed.
  2. Adjust the support, rib, and plate thicknesses.
  3. Adjust Lip angle, which determines how much of a grip your hangar has on the board.
  4. Visualise the setup of both hangars with your truck dimensions in the Draw section.
  5. Tweak the Rib angle if you want a smooth transition at the bottom of the Upright.
  6. Finally turn on Smooth. This may take a while to calculate. Up to 5 mins so be patient and turn it off if you want to make more adjustments.

Customize it until you get what you need.

  • Will print on small or large beds.
  • Does not need support.
  • Wheel sizes from 40-100mm in diameter.

Suggest you use a hex infill for strength, especially if you want the thinner support sections and rib.
[Edit: - added an image showing strain guage at 12 kilos. but hang tested it at 15kilos(33lbs) for a single. so 30kg or 66lbs for two hangars. Pretty much OK for your average board, raincoats, and extra batteries :)) ]

100-110C in a toaster oven for an hour and let cool.

title: Adjustable Mini Quad Runcam Mount (GoPro style Mount)

description.text:
Runcam 2 mount based of off SnappyFPV's Runcam 2 Diatone Crusader mount. Made to use gopro mounting sytem - you'll need the gopro bolt and nut (preferably the short bolt handle thing as opposed to the standard longer one).

The base of the mount was designed to fit a custom designed quadcopter of mine (CQ MK3), which is a one-off. I've included the .skp sketchup files if you want to edit it to fit the dimensions of whatever you are mounting it on. Otherwise the camera mount section itself will fit on any gopro mount.

Ideally print with flexible material for top and rigid for bottom. I printed with Taulman Nylon 910 and it works beautifully. All you need to do is cut on of the pillars next to the camera lens (as can be seen in pic above) in order to slide the Runcam 2 inside, as while Taulman's Nylon 910 is flexible its not flexible enough to slot into the top.

I placed the camera mount sideways on the build sideways, and the base with its base downwards. Print with whatever infill you like, obviously the greater the better if you don't care about weight and prefer strength. Then again Nylon 910 is ridiculously tough, so mini-quad guys can get away with much lower infill if they use this filament.

description.text:
I have been collecting minis for the quite a while now, and one common truth seems to be that in the world of fantasy miniature, there are very few minis that represent commoners, tavern folk, and everyday people. I have been slowly converting very cheap, easy to find HeroClix minis into commoners for my games. I will be making printable accessories to convert these minis to fill towns and taverns.

First up is converting a Poison Ivy HeroClix mini into a simple Bar Maid. I picked up a Poison Ivy HeroClix from Troll and Toad http://www.trollandtoad.com/p1089700.html

Simply cut her off of the HeroClix base and glue her down to the printable mini base. Print out one of the Trays and glue it to her hand (you may want to paint it first). If you wish, you can paint her cloths. That's it. You're done.

I am also using all the leftover trays as simple drink trays for tavern tables.

Also Pictured are several other HeroClix minis I have converted into Tavern Folks. I simply cut off their weapons (if they had any), cut them off of the HeroClix base and glued them onto a printable base. Then glued a tankard to their hand.

Huge shout out to Talismancer https://www.thingiverse.com/Talismancer/designs for letting me play around with one of his designs!

title: ANYCUBIC END EFECTOR FOR PCB PRINTING

description.text: Get ready with all the parts along with the additional requirements on each parts. Assemble the part according to the sketch on the lower left corner on the sketch image. Place the copper plate on the working area. Upload the gcode file for PCB plotting. After the process is done you get a PCB, where you can solder the remaining electronic devices to get a circuit board.

Requirements
  • Shaft. Dimension: 6mm (Diameter), Material: Stainless Steel(SS), Length: 8cm
  • Circlips. Inner Diameter: 5mm , Qty: 2
  • Metal Washers: Inner Diamerter: 6.5mm, Outer Diameter:12. Qty: 3
  • Spring: Inner Diameter: 6mm
  • Shaft Holder. (3D Printed). File Attached as: Upper_part.stl
  • M3 SS Bolts. Qty: 4
  • Metal Washers. Inner Diameter :3mm Qty: 4
  • Fiber washers. Inner Diameter: 3mm Qty: 4
  • Spring Washers. Inner Diamerter: 3mm. Qty: 4
  • M3 Nuts. Qty: 4

Making Parts Ready 1: The File attached under the name of Upper_part.stl must be printed before we start assembling stuffs (Two of such parts is needed). This might take a moment but please be patient.
2: After the Parts have been successfully printed, We need to calibrate the hole of 6mm which s there right on the middle of the work-piece. For this Take the 6mm shaft and heat it a little ( The Process which was used meanwhile was placing the Shaft on the Drill, Rotating it at its maximum speed and Applying Sandpaper on its Surface. This Process will not only heat he shaft but also will smooth the shafts surface.) The heated shaft is inserted in the hole so that the shaft moves through the hole with less resistance.
3: Making Circlip Slots, Mark 10mm and 50mm from one side of the rod (Let this side be named as A and other be B) Make the slots for the Circlip slots on those marked points. The method which we used was placing the shaft on the drill and then placing a hacksaw blade on the marked line)
4: Sharpening the Shaft, the other side of the shaft i.e B has to be sharpen. We used an angle grinder with a buffing blade, placed the shaft with some constant angle and rotated the shaft.
5: Ready the copper plate, The copper plate of required dimension was sliced out and one face of it is perfectly sketched with black sketch pen.

Gather your Tools

Bolt both the 3D printed part, sandwiched between the bed. Apply Fiber washer below bolt head and Metal Washer right before spring washer and nut. Rest of the part should be assembled as the sketch image attached.

Feel free to ask any doubts regarding the assembly.

description.text:
I designed and printed this support at the request of a friend who wanted a rack to display 18 large "plastic test tubes" filled with eatable gelatin to be part of a children's party table decor. The final result was great and it was great fun for the kids.

These files include everything you need for the support, but the test tubes are not included (we bought them on the local market but I guess they are like this one: http://a.co/5AekGUA ).

Because the larger lower disk is too big, I divided it into two halves that need to be glued together. The two halves are identical, so you just need to print such file twice. Once you insert the large disk through the top cylinder, I suggest you also glue them together. The small disk on the top doesn't have to be glued to the cylinder, but if you choose to do so, please remember to do it after you've inserted the large disk.

I used rafts and full supports to print all parts except for the small disk.

This is one of my first designs made on Autodesk Fusion 360... a very good upgrade from Tinkercad that I've been using so far. Fusion 360 definitively allow for a level of complexity that is much more than enough considering what domestic 3D printing machines are able to do. Hope you enjoy it.
